<HEAD>Snakebite Victim Resting Comfortably, But Remains In Danger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A snake-venom researcher bitten by a deadly
viper rested comfortably Sunday while doctors considered whether to
treat him with antivenins from Iran, England and the Soviet Union, a
hospital spokesman said.
   William E. Haast, 78, remained in serious but stable condition at
the University of Utah Health Sciences Center after being bitten on
the left hand Tuesday by a Pakistani pit viper, also known as a
saw-scaled viper, said hospital spokesman John Dwan.
   ``Mr. Haast is resting very comfortably, eating and chatting with
friends,'' Dwan said. ``He's just in danger, if you will.''
   Haast, director of the Miami Serpentarium Laboratories at the
university's Research Park, has been bitten 148 times by snakes and
is immune to the venom of dozens of reptiles. But he had no immunity
to the viper's bite and checked himself into the hospital Wednesday.
   The saw-scaled viper's venom attacks its victim's ability to
produce fibrinogen, an element of blood that regulates coagulation.
A lack of fibrinogen can cause uncontrolled bleeding.
   Dwan said the level of Haast's fibrinogen had been improving
slightly although it remained ``dangerously low'' Sunday.
   Doctors were replacing Haast's fibrinogen with transfusions and
it appeared his system had begun to produce it again, Dwan said.
   He said Haast's blood was being analyzed every four hours, and
that by late Saturday his fibrogen level was about one-third of
normal. On Wednesday, he said, ``for all intents and purposes (it
was) at zero.''
   Haast's plight prompted an effort by Stephen Studdernt, special
assistant to President Bush, to coordinate the acquisition of
antivenins from the three nations and expedite shipment to Utah.
   Dwan said antivenins from Iran and England had arrived, but he
did not know if the one from the Soviet Union had. The antivenin
from Iran was more specifically made to counteract venom from the
species of viper that bit Haast, he said.
   However, he said doctors were ``very leery about giving
medication to someone from a source about which we know very little
about.''
   Antivenins are made from horse serum and can cause negative side
effects such as lung and kidney problems, he said.
   ``We want to emphasize the fact that we're grateful to everyone
who went to such great lengths to get the antivenin,'' Dwan said.
``The decision on whether to use them or not will be based on Mr.
Haast's condition. Hopefully we won't have to use them.''
   Haast had been treated earlier with antivenins from California's
San Diego Zoo and from a lab in Los Angeles, but Dwan said Saturday
he had not been given antivenins for about 24 hours.
   He said doctors also had contacted scientists and physicans in
Europe, across the United States and Australia to discuss treatment.
   ``It's a special kind of snake, with a special kind of poison,
and the immunology is complicated,'' Dwan said. ``Our physicians
aren't just winging it on their own.''
   Studdert said the Iranian government apparently did not interfere
with the shipment of the antivenin despite the strained relations
between the two nations. Iranian leader Ayatolla Khomeini has often
called the United States the ``great Satan.''
   The Pakistani pit viper is one of 1,000 exotic, poisonous snakes
Haast keeps at the laboratory, where their venom is extracted for
sale to universities and health organizations for research and the
manufacture of antivenins.
</TEXT>
