<LEADPARA>  Neither sleet nor snow nor rain nor dark of night will keep a letter carrier
from his appointed rounds. And you can add rattlesnakes to the list.;    Ed
Brown of Brady, a 40-year-old contract letter carrier, says he's glad to be
alive after four days in the hospital as a result of his tussle with a rattler
on his rounds last week.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  General News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VENOMOUS SNAKE FAILS TO RATTLE TEXAS MAIL
CARRIER  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     He started his route as usual last Monday in northern McCulloch County, he
said, and was planning to finish in time for his mother's funeral at 3 p.m.;  
 "I had my radio on and when I pulled up beside one of the boxes, I
accidentally dropped a piece of mail. I should have known better, but I never
thought about anything except picking up that letter," Brown said.;    He
opened the car door, leaned out and stuck his right hand into the weeds to
find the letter. "I saw a quick movement at the same time I felt a bite, but
between the radio and the noise of the car's motor, I did not hear a warning
rattle of the snake," he said.;    "I looked at my hand and saw blood coming
out and it immediately began hurting. I know this sounds stupid, but I kept on
delivering the mail for the next 20 or more minutes," Brown said.;    He said
his swelling hand kept hurting and he tried to suck venom out of it.;    "When
I arrived in Lohn (20 miles from Brady), I knew I needed help. Then I
remembered I had heard that the latest treatment for snakebite is to use
high-voltage electricity, such as a spark plug or a cattle prod on the bite. I
didn't have a cattle prod, so I pulled a wire off the distributor and held my
hand against the distributor post," he said.  </TEXT>
