<HL> Bangladesh Gets $236 Million in Aid For Flood Relief </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> FREST </CO>
<DATELINE> DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP)  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flood waters began to recede Sunday, and the government said it has received $236 million in aid to fight the destruction and disease caused by recent floods. 

   Thousands of lives were threatened by diarrhea caused by drinking water contaminated with sewage and garbage washed up by raging flood waters, health officials said. 

   More than 200,000 people have contracted the disease and at least 123 have died from it, said the officials, who requested anonymity. 
The disease kills by dehydration. 

   As river levels began to fall after two weeks of flooding, many residents returned to their homes, said officials at the Flood Control Center. 
They said they expect the water level to soon begin to drop quickly. 

   The floods covered three-quarters of the nation and 53 of the country's 64 districts, with a population of 30 million, said Information Minister Mahbubur Rahman. 

   He said 866 people have died of drowning, snakebites and disease. 
The government figure is considered low, and newspapers estimate at least 1,532 people have died. 

   "The world has responded promptly and generously to our appeal for help to the flood victims," Mr. Rahman said. 

   He said the U.S. pledged $150 million in aid on Saturday, in addition to $2.6 million committed earlier. 
More funds and relief supplies have arrived from Japan, the Soviet Union, the European Economic Community, India, Pakistan and Saudi Arabia, among others, he said. 

   The Soviet Union has offered 100 tents, 1,000 blankets and 100 tons of medicine, he said. 

   Danielle Mitterrand, wife of the French President Francois Mitterrand, will visit the flood-affected areas during her four-day tour. 

   Mr. Rahman estimated the damage from flooding would exceed $1.4 billion and that 6,000 to 10,000 tons of grains stored in warehouses were damaged or destroyed by water. 

   The government of Hussain Muhammad Ershad is struggling with a shortage of helicopters and boats to get food and medicine to people stranded in the countryside. 

   Hundreds of volunteer organizations, many run by Christian missionaries, are aiding in the relief effort, but reporters have visited areas where the first relief supplies didn't arrive until Saturday. 

   Mr. Rahman said, however, that the country has enough food to meet immediate needs and that the government would ensure "that nobody dies of starvation during the floods." 

