<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rural Texans stubbornly stayed by their homes as
the Trinity River _ swollen from the worst northern Texas flooding
in more than 80 years _ rolled southward toward the Gulf of Mexico
today.
   Elsewhere, a reservoir on the Oklahoma line began falling after
hitting a record of more than 27 feet above normal, and snakebites
were on the rise in Arkansas, where flooding has forced the
evacuation of more than 300 homes and driven the reptiles from
nesting areas.
   The Arkansas River hit a record 27.6 feet _ 3.6 feet above flood
stage _ today at Little Rock.
   Thirteen deaths have been blamed on the weather in the past two
weeks, one in Oklahoma and the rest in Texas.
   Northern Texas has had 22.06 inches of rainfall in the first
four months of 1990, the most since 1922. The result: the worst
flooding since 1908.
   Light rain fell today in eastern Texas and there was a chance of
thunderstorms in the Dallas area Wednesday, but National Weather
Service meteorologist John Cockrell said that should not compound
the already severe flooding.
   In Texas, flood warnings for people and livestock were issued
for today as the Trinity River engulfed homes, pastures and fields
south of Dallas.
   At least 150 people were evacuated and main roads closed in
Trinidad, 60 miles southeast of Dallas. Near Palestine, 90 miles
below Dallas, about 50 homes were destroyed or severely damaged in
the community of Long Lake, where the Trinity, usually a few
hundred feet across, had bulged to about two miles.
   ``We can't tell exactly how many residences are affected yet,
because we can't count underwater,'' said Bill Walters, manager of
a Red Cross shelter set up in a campground.
   While about 80 people had been evacuated from Long Lake by late
Monday, many were reluctant to leave, Walters said. ``These people
are pretty stubborn, as all Texans are. They think they can stick
it out, but they really can't do it,'' he said.
   As the flooding moved downstream, the Red Cross sent teams to
prepare shelters. Many farm-to-market roads and some major highways
were closed.
   Lake Texoma on the Oklahoma line fell half a foot Monday after
cresting at a record 644.76 feet above sea level, the first time
since 1957 that water flowed out the spillways.
   Mike McCoy of the Army Corps of Engineers said will take up to
two months for the lake to return to a ``decent'' level as the
Corps plans to lower i by 6 to 9 inches a day.
   A preliminary survey Sunday found 83 homes at least partially
submerged in Oklahoma's Marshall County, which is partly cut off
from the outside by the swollen lake.
   Highway flooding made life strange for Judy Peterson, who works
in Madill, Okla.
   Instead of simply driving the 18 miles from her home on Sand
Point to the office, she and her husband must take a boat a
half-mile and then drive a circuitous 56-mile route around the
northern edge of Lake Texoma and back to Madill. They'd been doing
that for a week as of Monday.
   ``It's really getting old,'' she said.
   In central Arkansas, the rising waters of the Arkansas River
have driven snakes from their homes. A hospital at Pine Bluff,
which normally treats one snakbite victim a week, has treated eight
in the last week. Spokesman Bill Cheatham said most were bitten by
copperheads, but no one was seriously hurt.
   Water was reported up to 3{ feet deep in homes in the Pine Bluff
area.
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton added two more counties to last
week's disaster declaration Monday, bringing the total to 29. An
estimated 325 houses were evacuated in six counties, officials said.
   Officials said the flooding along the Arkansas River was the
worst since a 1927 rampage that prompted construction of many of
the levees along the river.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

