<LEADPARA>  MY GREAT grandmother and grandfather threw all their belongings in the back of
a covered wagon and drove half way across this country to settle in Oregon. A
hundred and fifty years later we barely have room in the trunk of our car for
two small suitcases.;    The lack of trunk space began a few years ago when my
wife volunteered to be Building Warden at the place where she works. The
Building Warden, a charming sounding title that my kids have shortened for
home use, is "responsible for overseeing safety in the workplace." Basically,
this meant that my wife was responsible for fire evacuation and
squeeze-under-the-desk drills.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Extra  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WE'RE BESTED BY PREPARATIONS FOR THE WORST  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Also ran in EX2/1, EX3/2  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Even though my wife lost her volunteer position after she dived under her
desk during the October 1989 earthquake and wouldn't come out, remnants of
warden training linger in our trunk.;    It's crammed with metallic-looking
blankets, bottled water, first aid supplies, tools, a shovel, a pick, rope, an
emergency flag, flares, extra shoes, crossing guard-type rain parkas, the list
goes on and on.;    Although we didn't plan to, we recently had an opportunity
to inventory the gear. On a weekend trip we stayed at a hotel where they have
guys dressed in band uniforms who take your luggage to your room while you
check in.;    Since none of us stayed with the car, a young man with "Andy"
embroidered on his uniform surgically emptied the trunk and took everything to
our room. The room resembled The Hyatt Touch at a Mt. Everest base camp.;   
Now I don't want to insinuate that each of us shouldn't be prepared for
possible disaster. What I want to point out is that there must be a limit
somewhere. My wife contends that she has already limited herself to the very
basics.;    "We could really use a small cook stove, a lantern and a snake-
bite kit," she told me. "We should also increase the dried food to feed four
of us for four days. We've got to look out for our family.";    Though, should
disaster strike I know what would happen. My wife is a very giving person. If
we were stranded with 70 other people, regular folks who carry golf clubs and
a spare tire in their trunk, I know that she would open our cache and share
the supplies. I'd be left with the package marked "Freeze-Dried Beef
Surprise." You know the old joke. The surprise is that there isn't any beef in
the meal.;    Late at night, when I'm lying in bed recounting the day's
activities and planning the next day, my mind sometimes wanders to the trunk
and I can't help thinking that what we really need is a small trailer for our
emergency stockpile.;    So keep an eye out for a man in a four-door sedan
pulling a small trailer. If it looks like me you'll know that I again have a
trunk, and also rest assured that should disaster strike I've got tools,
water, blankets, flares and. . . .  </TEXT>
