<HEAD>Winter in Hong Kong Means It's Time For Snake Soup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WONG SAU-YING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people's idea of Yuletide fun is to watch
the waiter bite the head off a live viper and pluck out the
still-squirming serpent's bladder. The slippery green organ is then
eaten raw.
   Sure, not everyone will cotton to that bitter flavor, but they
say snake enhances sexual prowess, so what's not to like?
   For one thing, snakes may be threatened with extinction, Hong
Kong's government has declared.
   On Friday, the government adopted a law that requires snake
dealers to apply for import and export licences for king cobras,
Asiatic cobras and Oriental rat snakes. Failure to comply could
bring fines of up to $3,200 and up to six months in jail.
   Chan Ping-kwong, spokesman for the Agriculture and Fisheries
Department, said the government would collect data on snake imports
to make sure the reptiles aren't in danger of extinction.
   More than 100,000 snakes are imported by Hong Kong each year,
mostly from China, Chan said.
   Serpent eating is a feature of social life in the British
colony, especially during winter when the vipers are reportedly
tastiest, having gorged themselves to prepare for hibernation.
   Snake soup is a staple of business banquets this time of year,
and trade unions are organizing year-end snake feasts to kick off
an election campaign for the legislature and other local offices
next year.
   The most common snake dish is a soup, cooked with mushrooms,
bamboo shoots and dried orange peels. The potion is reputed to
speed the metabolism and improve male sexual performance.
   Another favorite, snakes' skin soaked in malt wine, is believed
to have calming effects similar to that of tranquilizers.
   Perhaps the most spectacular way of eating snake is swallowing
raw bladders. The dark green organ is extremely slippery and has an
intensely bitter taste.
   To show how fresh their product is, Hong Kong vendors bite the
snake's head off in front of customers, who get to watch the body
of the reptile wriggle through the vendor's fingers as he searches
for the organ.
   The conservation organization World Wide Fund For Nature said it
supported the government's licensing decision.
   ``If unrestricted trade continues, snakes will one day become
endangered,'' said Amy Lau, the fund's conservation officer in Hong
Kong.
   Snake trader Tam Sun, who runs a small shop in downtown Hong
Kong that sells snake soup, said he has no choice but to pass on
the cost of the new import license to his customers, who now pay $2
for a bowl.
   ``Our profit margin is already pretty narrow,'' Tam said, after
biting off the head of a green snake. ``Prices of snake soup will
go up 30 percent.''
